Two traffic analysis periods are evaluated in this report to identify improvements to the local
roadway system necessary to address project impacts. The first period assesses the local
roadway needs without the proposed project, while the second analysis period addresses the
build-out of the project which is expected to occur around 2009.

Capacity analyses were then conducted at each of the study area intersections using analysis
methods documented in the Highway Capacity Manual, 2003 by the Transportation Research
Board. These analyses use the existing traffic volumes and intersection lane geometry to
develop a level of service (LOS), a measure of the ease of traffic flow through an intersection.
Level of service A represents relatively uninterrupted flow with little or no vehicle delay, while
LOS F represents undue delay and excessive congestion.
Using these criteria, the existing traffic volumes, the existing signal timing and the intersection
lane assignments, capacity analyses of these intersections were conducted. The two

U L L E V I G
When evaluating the transportation needs for future time periods, it is important to understand
how the traffic that is already on the roadway system is expected to grow. Based on comments
from the City, traffic in the vicinity of the site is projected to grow at an average rate of
approximately 1 percent per year. This growth rate was used to forecast the background traffic
volumes. In addition, traffic volumes from the Riverclay and Frontview Crescent developments
were also included as part of the background traffic. These developments are expected to
include a total of 100 condominium units between them. Traffic volumes for the 2009
background scenario can be seen on Figure 3.
Once the future background volumes had been determined, a level of service analysis was
completed for the 2009 background scenario. The results of this analysis can be seen on
Figure 3 and level of service worksheets can be found in Appendix C. As can be seen on this
figure, both the signalized and stop-controlled intersections are anticipated to operate at LOS C
or better during the AM and PM peak hours.

page.text: The total estimated traffic volumes for the 2009 scenario are the compilation of the estimated
background traffic volumes and the vehicle activity projections for the project site. Figure 6
shows the estimates of total traffic at the major intersections of the study area. In addition, as
with background traffic, a level of service analysis was completed for the 2009 total traffic
scenario. The results of this analysis can be seen on Figure 6 and level of service worksheets
can be found in Appendix D. As can be seen on this figure, both the signalized and stop-
controlled intersections are anticipated to continue to operate at LOS C or better during the AM
and PM peak hours with the addition of site traffic.
Warrant 3 (Peak Hour) from the Manual on Uniform Traffic Control Devices (MUTCD) was
reviewed in order to determine if signals might be warranted at any of the unsignalized study
intersections in the near future. Based on a review of the criteria, none of the unsignalized
intersections within the study area are expected to warrant signalization.

Lane Geometry and Levels of Service
U L L E V I G
The proposed Pinnacle development is located to the west of I-25 and to the southeast of the
Avenue intersection. The development is proposed to include 350
apartment units. This land use is projected to generate approximately 2,350 daily vehicle-trips,
about 179 vehicle-trips during the AM peak hour and about 217 vehicle-trips during the PM peak
hour at the site access points.
Access to the proposed development would be provided via Front View Crescent, Bryant Street
and River Drive. The site access to River Drive is proposed to be a right-in/right-out/left-in that
will include a pork chop island and signage to encourage site vehicles from using River Drive to
access Clay Street. In addition, at the intersection of 23
Avenue and River Drive, which is
expected to be Building One’s main access to the external roadway network, the sight distance
to the west is obstructed both by vehicles parked on street and vegetation. Consideration should
be given to either removing a few on-street parking spaces or some of the vegetation in the area
For analysis purposes it was assumed that the eastbound and westbound approaches at the
Avenue and Clay Street intersection are single lane approaches even though it is generally
possible for through movements to get by left turning vehicles as long as the left turn queue
does not exceed two vehicles. In the event that the left turn queue regularly exceeds two
vehicles, one or two on-street parking spaces could be removed to provide more room for
through traffic. After completing the analyses, good levels of service can be obtained at the
project intersections without any roadway improvements. The levels of service at the study
intersections are C or better with and without the proposed Pinnacle development.
